Introduction


The goal of this project is to use SQL and R to answer business questions and do some data analysis. Weâll be using a modified version of a database called Chinook, provided by Dataquest. This database contains information about a fictional digital music shop, its customers, employees, sales, etc. The information is contained in eleven tables, which can be visualized in the schema diagram below.

This is an expansion of a guided project from the Data Analyst in R career path in Dataquest. More information about the database can be found on its website at https://github.com/lerocha/chinook-database


Helper functions


Letâs start by creating a helper function that allows us to connect to the database, run SQL queries, disconnect and get the resulting output.

# loading required libraries

library(DBI) 
library(RSQLite)
library(knitr) # kable wrapper function makes tables look nicer
# run_query helper function

run_query <- function(query) {
  conn <- dbConnect(SQLite(), 'chinook.db')
  result <- dbGetQuery(conn, query)
  dbDisconnect(conn)
  return(result)
}

Now letâs check if our function works by running a sample query.

Looks good! The next step is creating a function that simply displays all tables in the database, using our previous helper function to run the necessary query.

# show_tables helper function

show_tables <- function() {
  q = "SELECT name, type FROM sqlite_master WHERE type IN ('table', 'view')"
  return(run_query(q))
}

Letâs run it to see if itâs working.

Choosing new albums to be added to the store


The Chinook record store has just signed a deal with a new record label, and weâre in charge of choosing the first three albums to be added to the store. There are four albums to choose from, and all four are by artists who donât have any tracks in the store right now. Below is the list of artist names and the genre of music they produce:

Artist Name Genre
Regal Hip-Hop
Red Tone Punk
Meteor and the Girls Pop
Slim Jim Bites Blues

The record label specializes in artists from the USA, and they have given Chinook some money to advertise the new albums in the USA. To aid in selecting albums, weâre interested in finding out which genres sell the best in the USA. In order to do that, we are going to write a query that returns each genre, with the number of tracks sold in the USA, both in absolute numbers and in percentages. Weâll store the result in a variable so that we can better inspect the data and visualize it.

q <- "
  WITH tracks_sold_usa AS
    (
     SELECT
       g.name genre_name,
       SUM(il.quantity) tracks_sold
     FROM invoice i
     INNER JOIN invoice_line il ON i.invoice_id = il.invoice_id
     INNER JOIN track t ON il.track_id = t.track_id
     INNER JOIN genre g ON t.genre_id = g.genre_id
     WHERE billing_country = 'USA'
     GROUP BY 1
     ORDER BY 2 DESC
    )
  SELECT
    genre_name,
    tracks_sold,
    CAST(tracks_sold AS FLOAT) /
      (
       SELECT
         SUM(il.quantity)
       FROM invoice_line il
       INNER JOIN invoice i ON il.invoice_id = i.invoice_Id
       WHERE billing_country = 'USA'
      ) * 100 pct
  FROM tracks_sold_usa
  ORDER BY 2 DESC
"

genre_df <- run_query(q)

Evaluating sales support agentsâ performance


The next issue we are going to address is sales support agentsâ performance. Each customer for the Chinook store gets assigned to a sales support agent within the company when they first make a purchase. We have been asked to analyze the purchases of customers belonging to each employee to see if any sales support agent is performing either better or worse than the others.

Letâs start by writing a query that finds the total dollar amount of sales assigned to each agent and then plot the results.

q <- "
  WITH sales_per_employee AS
  (
    SELECT
      SUM(i.total) total_sales,
      e.employee_id
    FROM invoice i
    INNER JOIN customer c ON i.customer_id = c.customer_id
    INNER JOIN employee e ON c.support_rep_id = e.employee_id
    GROUP BY 2
  )
  
  SELECT
    e.employee_id,
    e.first_name || ' ' || e.last_name employee_name,
    spc.total_sales,
    e.hire_date,
    e.birthdate
  FROM sales_per_employee spc
  INNER JOIN employee e ON e.employee_id = spc.employee_id
  ORDER BY 3 DESC
"

sales_agents <- run_query(q) 
kable(sales_agents)

Letâs calculate a monthly average per agent to see if we get a more precise picture.

Before we proceed, since this is a fictional database, we need to do a little hack and check what is the latest day for which we have data. We can consider that date to be âtodayâ in our exercise and then use it to make our calculations.

# importing lubridate library to deal with dates

library(lubridate)
q <-"
SELECT
  invoice_date,
  COUNT(*)
FROM invoice
GROUP BY 1
ORDER BY 1 DESC
LIMIT 1;
"
results <- run_query(q)
today <- ymd(ymd_hms(results$invoice_date))
today
## [1] "2020-12-30"

Now that we know that âtodayâ, or the last day for which we have sales data is 2020/12/30, we can use that together with the hire dates and total sales from the agents to better measure their performance.

# importing dplyr for dataframe manipulation 

library(dplyr)
sales_agents <- sales_agents %>%
  mutate(days_since_hire = as.numeric(today - ymd(ymd_hms(hire_date)))) %>%
  mutate(sales_per_day = total_sales/days_since_hire,
         sales_per_month = sales_per_day * 30)
sales_agents %>%
  select(employee_name, sales_per_day, sales_per_month) %>%
  kable()

  labs(title = 'Average sales per month by employee',
       x = '',
       y = "average sales per month") +
theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5)) +

After calculating sales by monthly average by employee, we can see that Jane Peacock does seem to have a slightly better performance than the other two sales agents, although the difference is not really significant (just around 2$). Moreover, there is almost no difference between the performance of the other two employees.


Breaking down data by country


Our next task is analyze sales data for customers from each different country.

We are asked to provide the following information from each country:

  • total number of customers
  • total value of sales
  • average value of sales per customer
  • average order value

Where a country has only one customer, we should collect them into an âOtherâ group.

The results should be sorted by the total sales from highest to lowest, with the âOtherâ group at the very bottom.

Finally, we are asked to present that data in plots and to use it to find a country with potential for growth.

Letâs run a SQL query to retrieve the data and have a look at it.

q <- "

WITH 

  country_or_other AS
  (
   SELECT
     CASE 
       WHEN (
             SELECT COUNT(*)
             FROM customer
             WHERE country = c.country
             ) = 1 THEN 'Other'
       ELSE c.country
     END AS country,
     i.*
   FROM invoice i
   INNER JOIN customer c ON c.customer_id = i.customer_id
   
  ),

  customer_by_country AS
  (
   SELECT
     c.country,
     COUNT(DISTINCT(c.customer_id)) n_customers,
     SUM(c.total) total_sales,
     CAST(SUM(c.total) AS FLOAT) / COUNT(DISTINCT(c.customer_id)) avg_sales_per_customer,
     AVG(c.total) avg_order_value
  FROM country_or_other c
  GROUP BY 1
  ),
  
  sorted_other AS
  (
   SELECT
     c.*,
     CASE
       WHEN c.country = 'Other' THEN 1
       ELSE 0
     END AS sort
   FROM customer_by_country c 
  )
  
SELECT
  country,
  n_customers,
  total_sales,
  avg_sales_per_customer,
  avg_order_value
FROM sorted_other
ORDER BY sort, total_sales DESC
  
"
data_by_country <- run_query(q)
kable(data_by_country)

Whole album sales X individual tracks sales


The Chinook store is set up in a way that allows customers to make purchases in one of two ways:

  • Purchase a whole album
  • Purchase a collection of one or more individual tracks

The store does not let customers purchase a whole album, and then add individual tracks to that same purchase (unless they do that by choosing each track manually). When customers purchase albums, they are charged the same price as if they had purchased each of those tracks separately.

Management are currently considering changing their purchasing strategy to save money. The strategy they are considering is to purchase only the most popular tracks from each album from record companies, instead of purchasing every track from an album.

We have been asked to find out what percentage of purchases are individual tracks versus whole albums. Management can use this data to understand the effect this decision might have on overall revenue.

In order to satisfy this request, we need to classify each sale as a full album sale or individual tracks sale; calculate percentages; and finally come up with a conclusion about whether we should pursue this proposal from management or not.

q <- "
WITH album_or_single AS
  (

   SELECT
     DISTINCT(il.invoice_id),
     CASE
       WHEN
         (
         
          (
          SELECT
            t.track_id
          FROM track t
          WHERE album_id = ( 
                            SELECT
                              t2.album_id
                            FROM track t2
                            INNER JOIN invoice_line il2 ON t2.track_id = il2.track_id
                            WHERE il2.invoice_id = il.invoice_id
                            LIMIT 1
                            )
          EXCEPT
        
          SELECT
            t3.track_id
          FROM track t3
          INNER JOIN invoice_line il3 ON t3.track_id = il3.track_id
          WHERE il3.invoice_id = il.invoice_id
          
          )
          
          IS NULL
          
          AND
          
          (
          SELECT
            t3.track_id
          FROM track t3
          INNER JOIN invoice_line il3 ON t3.track_id = il3.track_id
          WHERE il3.invoice_id = il.invoice_id
          
          EXCEPT
          
          SELECT
            t.track_id
          FROM track t
          WHERE album_id = ( 
                            SELECT
                              t2.album_id
                            FROM track t2
                            INNER JOIN invoice_line il2 ON t2.track_id = il2.track_id
                            WHERE il2.invoice_id = il.invoice_id
                            LIMIT 1
                            )
          )
          IS NULL
          
         ) THEN 'album'
       ELSE 'single_track'
     END AS type_of_purchase
   FROM invoice_line il
  )

SELECT
  type_of_purchase,
  COUNT(invoice_id) number_of_purchases,
  (CAST(COUNT(invoice_id) AS FLOAT) /
    (SELECT COUNT(DISTINCT(invoice_id)) FROM invoice)
  ) * 100 percentage
FROM album_or_single
GROUP BY type_of_purchase
"
album_or_not <- run_query(q)
kable(album_or_not)
type_of_purchase number_of_purchases percentage
album 114 18.56678
single_track 500 81.43322

Although individual track sales account for around 81.43% of the total, we still have around 18.56% of whole album sales, which leads us to conclude that itâs not a good idea to stop offering full albums, since that could imply an important loss in revenue.
